===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|douten||lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|xno|en}} {{term|douter||lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|douter||lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|dubitare|lang=la}}. Replaced {{etyl|enm|-}} {{term|tweonien||to doubt|lang=enm}} (from {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|tweonian|twēonian|lang=ang}}, compare {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|tweo|twēo|doubt, duplicity|lang=ang}}). The modern spelling is probably under the influence of {{etyl|frm|en}} {{term|doubter|lang=frm}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{context|ambitransitive}} To lack confidence in; to [[disbelieve]], [[question]], or [[suspect]].
#: ''He '''doubted''' that was really what you meant.''
#* Hooker
#*: Even in matters divine, concerning some things, we may lawfully '''doubt'''{{...}}
#* Dryden
#*: To try your love and make you '''doubt''' of mine.
# {{context|archaic}} To [[fear]]; to [[suspect]].
#* '''1819''', Lord Byron, ''Don Juan'', I.186:
#*: He fled, like Joseph, leaving it; but there, / I '''doubt''', all likeness ends between the pair.

